    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-21T05:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-21T05:54:00-05:00" n="831"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d831">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.7490F/10–2144: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Eddy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-21T14:00:00+03:06"
                            >October 21, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>316. Saudi Government has not yet replied to question in Department’s 205,
                    October 6, 8 p.m.,<note n="95" xml:id="d831fn95">See footnote 94, <ref
                            target="#pg_761">p. 761</ref>.</note> but today British Chargé<note
                        n="96" xml:id="d831fn96">Robert E. Ellison.</note> informed me British
                    objected to Saudi radio station. He stated: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>That the commercial interests of Cable and Wireless were secondary to
                            primary objection based on security, in which American censors concurred
                            with British.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>That London’s objection was conveyed to Saudi Government 2 months ago.
                            It was not revealed because they hoped Aramco had forgotten about the
                            proposal and they hoped Americans would not press issue. However,
                            Foreign Ministry told British Legation that American Government had
                            asked for news of project and British decided to inform me.</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>That Aramco communications with United States of America could not be
                            very much delayed at present because Aramco sends most of its traffic at
                            deferred rate therefore need of direct channel not apparent.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>I stated that on the contrary direct channel to United States of America would be
                    very useful to Aramco and other Americans in Arabia and that I personally
                    regretted the unnecessary 2 months’ delay shortening the brief interval before
                    deadline of December 1.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Eddy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
